The K2-133 Exoplanetary System


Overview

K2-133 is a star with 0.46 times the mass of the Sun, and 0.46 times its radius. It is located 245.17 light years away from the solar system.

K2-133 is known to have 4 exoplanets in orbit around it.


Exoplanets in the K2-133 system


K2-133 b

K2-133 b was discovered by the K2 observatory, in 2018-01, using the transit method. Its semi-major axis is 0.03 astronomical units, as compared to Earth's which is 1 astronomical unit. The mass of K2-133 b is 2.360 times the mass of Earth. The radius of K2-133 b is 1.340 that of Earth. At 2.360 Earth masses, K2-133 b is a so called Super Earth. Super Earths could be terrestrial worlds like Earth, but they could also be ocean worlds or terrestrial worlds wrapped in a substantial atmosphere, in which case some refer to them as Mini Neptunes. No Super Earths are known to exist in our solar system, but if it exists, the so-called Planet Nine could very well be a super Earth, as it is hypothesized to have a mass between five and ten Earth masses.

The mass of K2-133 d is 4.675 times the mass of Earth. The radius of K2-133 d is 2.003 that of Earth. With a mass below 5 Earth masses, a density of 3.19, and a semi-major axis of 0.07487 astronomical units, K2-133 d could, potentially, be an ocean world - a planet with no dry land.
